Your problem is in swap2. In swap2, x and y are private to the function, having no relation to the x and y in main. So, you should pass x and y to the function:

    #include &lt;stdio.h&gt;

    void swap2(int x, int y);
    int main(){
        int x,y;
        printf(&quot;SWAP WITH USER INPUT\n&quot;);
        printf(&quot;Input 1st number: &quot;);
        scanf(&quot;%d&quot;,&amp;x);
        printf(&quot;Input 2nd number: &quot;);
        scanf(&quot;%d&quot;,&amp;y);
        printf(&quot;Values before swap x = %d and y = %d\n&quot;,x,y);
        swap2(x, y);
    }

    void swap2(int x, int y){
        int  z;
        z = x;
        x = y;
        y = z;
        printf(&quot;Values after swap x = %d and y = %d\n&quot;, x,y);
     }
Plus, you don&#39;t need stdlib.h.

The problem is, that you did not know that a variable declared and defined like that in `main()` is not accessible from functions calling by `main()` automatically and not to define them new to access the desired values.

You need to provide a calling function the required values (or at least pointers to them) to operate with those as arguments by the call of it, to use them inside there.

`swap2()` doesn&#180;t get `x` and `y` from your `main()` as arguments. you are declaring again different local variables of swap2 for `x` and `y`, which do not have the value assigned to from `main()`, just because it are other variables.

    void swap2()              // No incoming values as arguments
    {
       int x, y, z;           // You declaring here new local variables of x and y for swap2()
       z = x;
       x = y;
       y = z;
       printf(&quot;Values after swap x = %d and y = %d\n&quot;, x,y);
    }


Use it like that:

    void swap2(int x, int y) 
    {
       int z;

       z = x;
       x = y;
       y = z;

       printf(&quot;Values after swap x = %d and y = %d\n&quot;, x,y);
    }

and put the line 

````
swap2(x,y);
````
inside your `main()`, instead of

    swap2();

Hopefully, you have learned something new now ;-)

Please, note, that in your current implementation

     void swap2() {
       /* Local variables declarations */
       /* x, y, z are not from main    */
       int x, y, z;
       ...
     }

`x`, `y` and `z` are *local* *uninitialized* values; so you swap *trash* (all chances that `x == y == z == 0`). If you want to *swap* `x` and `y` values which are declared in `main`, you can operate with *pointers*, not *values*:

     int main() {
       ...
       printf(&quot;Values before swap x = %d and y = %d\n&quot;, x, y);
       /* Addresses of x and y */
       swap2(&amp;x, &amp;y);
       /* Now x and y swapped their values */
       printf(&quot;Values after swap x = %d and y = %d\n&quot;, x, y);
     }
    
     /* swap2 wants addresses of x and y, not their values */
     void swap2(int* x, int* y) {
         int z;  
        
         z = *x; /* z get a value at address of x      */
        *x = *y; /* put value at y address to x adress */
        *y = z;  /* put z at y address                 */ 
     }

**Outcome:**

     Values before swap x = 3 and y = 4
     Values after swap x = 4 and y = 3

If `swap2` should do nothing but print values in *different order*, just let it do it:

     int main() {
       ...
       printf(&quot;Values before swap x = %d and y = %d\n&quot;, x, y);
       /* we don&#39;t swap x, y but pring them in different order; no need in pointers */
       swap2(x, y);
     }

